WEBVTT

00:03.780 --> 00:06.772
["Wave of Mutilation"
by Rhett Miller playing]

00:29.500 --> 00:32.845
And what do you want?

00:32.900 --> 00:34.891
You.

00:36.940 --> 00:39.295
You're not getting divorced
because of me?

00:39.340 --> 00:41.035
No.

00:43.210 --> 00:44.199
No.

00:46.910 --> 00:49.299
Because...

00:49.350 --> 00:50.647
that would be
a bad idea.

00:50.700 --> 00:53.783
Why?

00:53.830 --> 00:55.821
Because I don't know
what we are yet.

00:55.880 --> 00:58.303
Well, I don't either,

00:58.360 --> 01:01.181
but I'm through
delaying anything.

01:01.230 --> 01:05.439
I've looked back at my life,
and every time

01:05.500 --> 01:07.104
I didn't say something I meant

01:07.150 --> 01:08.492
or waited for a better moment...

01:08.540 --> 01:09.495
[knocking on door]

01:09.540 --> 01:12.418
[sighs]

01:12.460 --> 01:14.018
I-I should go anyway.

01:14.070 --> 01:15.412
No, you're staying.

01:15.460 --> 01:17.416
And they can just wait
until I'm done.

01:17.460 --> 01:21.544
There is no better moment.

01:21.600 --> 01:24.296
That's the one thing--
the only thing I've discovered.

01:24.340 --> 01:25.989
Everything comes to an end.

01:26.040 --> 01:27.428
There's no better moment
than now.

01:27.470 --> 01:28.687
[knocking on door]

01:28.740 --> 01:30.423
GRACE: Mom, I need your help
with the flowers.

01:30.480 --> 01:32.163
[laughs]

01:34.790 --> 01:36.599
Alicia,

01:36.660 --> 01:37.877
we will talk.

01:41.490 --> 01:42.912
Okay.

01:42.970 --> 01:45.484
[clears throat]

01:48.190 --> 01:49.623
What's that?

01:49.670 --> 01:50.659
Um...

01:50.710 --> 01:54.362
It's just a--
it's a little present.

01:54.410 --> 01:57.755
Really, it...

01:57.810 --> 01:58.845
it's nothing.

02:00.680 --> 02:02.409
No, no, it...

02:02.470 --> 02:03.596
I'm sorry, it...

02:06.340 --> 02:07.819
...really is nothing.

02:07.860 --> 02:11.125
It's a deed to
some land on Mars.

02:12.950 --> 02:14.292
They're selling it online,

02:14.350 --> 02:18.081
so you own 500 acres
in the Valles Marineris.

02:18.130 --> 02:19.654
[knocking on door]

02:19.700 --> 02:21.691
GRACE: Seriously, Mom,
I can't get them all in.

02:21.750 --> 02:23.911
It was meant to be a joke.

02:23.960 --> 02:27.225
I'm sorry.
Here.

02:27.270 --> 02:29.261
Mom!

02:29.320 --> 02:31.572
I will call you.

02:41.240 --> 02:45.597
Wow, that is a lot of flowers.

02:45.640 --> 02:47.460
Hey, Jason.
Hi.

02:47.510 --> 02:49.558
Do you want me to help
you bring these in?

02:49.600 --> 02:51.682
Oh, no, thanks,
I think we're sending them back.

02:51.730 --> 02:53.516
Mom, the florist
sent us funeral flowers.

02:53.560 --> 02:56.290
They got our order mixed
up with somebody else.

02:56.350 --> 02:57.738
JASON:
Okay, uh...

02:57.780 --> 02:59.600
Good luck.
Have a great party.

02:59.650 --> 03:01.083
GRACE:
Thanks, bye.

03:01.130 --> 03:03.086
Mom, they said that they
knocked, but nobody answered,

03:03.130 --> 03:04.563
so they just left them here.

03:04.610 --> 03:06.521
I think they knew they
were the wrong ones.

03:06.570 --> 03:08.299
Mom?

03:12.060 --> 03:14.096
Oh, my gosh, those
arefuneral flowers.

03:14.150 --> 03:15.481
What are we gonna do?

03:15.540 --> 03:17.622
I told them that it was
for Grandma and Howard's...

03:17.670 --> 03:18.625
what's it called?

03:18.670 --> 03:19.625
A ketubah signing.

03:19.670 --> 03:20.978
It's like a wedding contract.

03:21.020 --> 03:22.749
Right, I think I called it
a wedding reception.

03:22.810 --> 03:24.414
Well, we have an hour.

03:24.460 --> 03:28.066
I have to get myself changed,
get the food out, decorate.

03:28.120 --> 03:30.372
Let's get these inside and
then you call the florist.

03:30.420 --> 03:32.115
You don't think we could pass
them off as celebratory, can we?

03:32.160 --> 03:33.639
Like white for spring?

03:33.690 --> 03:35.373
It would be funny if we try.

03:35.430 --> 03:37.421
I don't think funny's
what we're going for.

03:41.090 --> 03:43.081
[phones ringing,
indistinct chatter]

03:51.310 --> 03:53.266
[door closes]

03:53.320 --> 03:54.571
Exactly the man I wanted to see.

03:54.620 --> 03:56.531
I thought I was meeting
with Mike.

03:56.580 --> 03:59.094
You were. Things
have changed.

03:59.150 --> 04:01.015
Ignore me, this is Dad's thing.Yeah, put your earbuds in.

04:01.060 --> 04:02.539
[scoffs]This is going to trial.

04:02.590 --> 04:04.319
I know.

04:04.370 --> 04:06.588
The governor doesn't want
you to work on his case.

04:06.630 --> 04:08.894
And part of our strategy
is built on a speedy trial.

04:08.940 --> 04:10.714
Uh, Peter needs to
get back to work

04:10.770 --> 04:12.544
and he can't do
that with this...

04:12.600 --> 04:13.544
Cloud?

04:13.600 --> 04:14.726
Yes, yes, with this cloud

04:14.770 --> 04:18.638
hanging over him, so...

04:18.690 --> 04:20.112
I need your help.

04:20.170 --> 04:23.424
You know I'm not
the best person to do this.

04:23.480 --> 04:24.424
Yes, I do,

04:24.480 --> 04:27.904
and that is why I need you.

04:27.960 --> 04:32.169
I want you to prove
that Peter is guilty.

04:32.220 --> 04:33.619
Why?

04:33.660 --> 04:36.265
We're being offered a
plea bargain by the AUSA.

04:36.310 --> 04:37.527
It makes no sense.

04:37.580 --> 04:38.615
Three years in prison?

04:38.660 --> 04:40.400
The evidence doesn't support it.

04:40.450 --> 04:43.089
Get the discovery.I did, and I'm not
getting a straight answer

04:43.150 --> 04:44.310
from Peter's investigators--

04:44.370 --> 04:45.314
they're being far
too deferential--

04:45.370 --> 04:47.930
so I need you to be tough.

04:47.980 --> 04:50.141
Show me why he's guilty.

04:59.690 --> 05:02.204
[sighs]

05:13.960 --> 05:15.780
Hey, food's here.
What's that?

05:15.830 --> 05:16.819
Uh, nothing.

05:16.880 --> 05:18.529
Any luck with the flowers?

05:18.570 --> 05:19.912
No, they said
that it's our fault.

05:19.970 --> 05:22.313
That we've ordered
the bereavement array.

05:22.360 --> 05:24.408
I said that there's a_ funeral
somewhere that's getting flowers

05:24.450 --> 05:26.406
that say, "Congratulations,
Howard and Jackie."

05:26.450 --> 05:27.405
[both laugh]

05:27.450 --> 05:28.439
You look really pretty.

05:28.500 --> 05:30.013
Why, thank you.
So do you.

05:30.060 --> 05:31.015
Thank you.

05:31.060 --> 05:32.015
Let me see that.
What is it?

05:32.070 --> 05:33.321
Oh, it's nothing.

05:36.680 --> 05:40.150
It's a deed to land on Mars.

05:40.200 --> 05:42.282
Why do you have a deed
to land on Mars?

05:42.340 --> 05:44.240
[chuckles]

05:44.300 --> 05:46.029
I have no idea.

05:46.080 --> 05:47.775
It was a gift.

05:47.820 --> 05:50.380
What, from a 13-year-old?

05:50.430 --> 05:52.512
Or 12.
Maybe he was 12 years old.

05:52.560 --> 05:54.084
"The Florrick Homestead."

05:54.130 --> 05:55.438
[both chuckle]
Yeah.

05:55.480 --> 05:56.868
Pretty weird gift, isn't it?

05:56.920 --> 05:58.876
Yeah, who gave it to you?

05:58.920 --> 06:00.524
Someone from work.

06:00.570 --> 06:03.038
I mean, 500 acres.

06:03.100 --> 06:05.261
That's a lot of acres.

06:05.320 --> 06:06.355
You're right.

06:06.400 --> 06:09.016
It could've been 50 acres.

06:09.060 --> 06:10.618
You could ranch there.

06:10.670 --> 06:12.399
I could raise a family.

06:12.450 --> 06:15.669
[both laugh]

06:15.720 --> 06:17.062
ZACH:
Hello? Mom?

06:17.110 --> 06:19.419
[gaSPSJ

06:20.460 --> 06:23.281
Aw. Thank you.

06:23.330 --> 06:24.285
For what?

06:24.340 --> 06:26.683
For coming home for this.

06:26.730 --> 06:27.981
And for wearing a tie.

06:28.030 --> 06:29.770
It was a long weekend.

06:29.820 --> 06:31.071
How's Grandma doing?She's happy.

06:31.120 --> 06:33.076
Good.

06:33.130 --> 06:35.473
Grace, hey.
Hey.

06:35.520 --> 06:37.033
We have funeral flowers.

06:37.090 --> 06:38.910
We do.
Why?

06:38.960 --> 06:41.428
Well, we thought we'd go
a different way.

06:41.480 --> 06:43.084
Okay, the guests are
coming in ten minutes.

06:43.140 --> 06:44.869
Let's try and pull
this together.

06:44.920 --> 06:46.091
So, I have
a surprise for you, Mom.

06:46.140 --> 06:48.096
Oh, is it a deed
to land on Mars?

06:48.140 --> 06:49.960
What?
ALICIA:
Nothing.

06:50.010 --> 06:51.830
Your sister's in a funny mood.

06:51.880 --> 06:53.051
What's the surprise?

06:53.100 --> 06:54.442
I can't tell you yet.

06:54.500 --> 06:55.922
You're flunking out.

06:55.980 --> 06:57.459
No.

06:57.500 --> 06:59.627
[snoring]

07:01.370 --> 07:03.543
You were snoring.

07:03.590 --> 07:05.319
Do we have a meeting?
Nope.

07:05.380 --> 07:08.338
Just dropped by.

07:08.380 --> 07:09.335
Here.

07:09.380 --> 07:10.631
It's a donut.

07:14.170 --> 07:17.424
I have another five hours
of work tonight, Jason.

07:17.480 --> 07:19.380
Whatever you want,

07:19.430 --> 07:20.988
can we do this another time?

07:21.040 --> 07:21.995
Governor Florrick.

07:22.050 --> 07:24.041
You?

07:24.090 --> 07:25.478
They must be paying you well.

07:25.530 --> 07:26.565
Did he do it?

07:26.620 --> 07:28.349
You mean did he tank
my prosecution

07:28.400 --> 07:30.743
in order to satisfy
one of his donors?

07:30.790 --> 07:32.439
Sure, let's start with that.You tell me.

07:32.490 --> 07:33.741
I had a strong case.

07:33.800 --> 07:36.837
Richard Locke shoots
his girlfriend Patty

07:36.890 --> 07:37.959
when she comes home one night.

07:38.020 --> 07:40.488
Two bullets in the chest.

07:40.540 --> 07:43.236
Look at the crime scene photos.

07:43.280 --> 07:45.066
Poor woman bled out.

07:45.110 --> 07:46.930
How was the scene?
Untouched.

07:46.980 --> 07:49.244
Locke said he didn't do it,

07:49.290 --> 07:50.678
but he was covered in blood.

07:53.030 --> 07:54.554
Who ran the case?

07:54.600 --> 07:56.989
A detective from the 32nd.

07:57.040 --> 07:59.383
Uh... Crowell.

07:59.430 --> 08:00.385
Rick Crowell?

08:00.430 --> 08:02.034
I know him.

08:02.090 --> 08:03.739
Yeah, he's not a cowboy.

08:03.780 --> 08:04.997
So it was a slam-dunk case.

08:05.040 --> 08:06.826
Till Peter got involved.

08:06.870 --> 08:08.861
See, he was
the new state's attorney.

08:08.920 --> 08:10.000
Came in and started
mIcromanagIng

08:10.050 --> 08:11.358
right from the start.

08:11.400 --> 08:13.004
"Are you sure
about the witnesses?"

08:13.050 --> 08:14.836
"Was he properly Mirandized?"

08:14.880 --> 08:16.529
"What about the blood?"
"Are you sure?"

08:16.580 --> 08:18.536
And were you sure?

08:18.580 --> 08:20.354
This shouldn't
have been a mistrial.

08:20.410 --> 08:22.708
Richard Locke should be
in prison right now.

08:22.760 --> 08:24.057
It was premeditated.

08:24.110 --> 08:25.498
But you know
what he isdoing right now?

08:25.540 --> 08:27.713
He got married a month ago.

08:27.760 --> 08:29.546
Tough thing being rich.

08:29.590 --> 08:33.151
Yup, I'm sure he's
all broken up on the inside.

08:33.200 --> 08:36.078
Thanks.

08:36.120 --> 08:37.109
Go back to sleep.

08:39.210 --> 08:40.165
Hey,

08:40.210 --> 08:41.723
promise me one thing.

08:41.780 --> 08:42.906
What?

08:42.950 --> 08:45.862
Don't get the governor off.

08:45.910 --> 08:46.865
[knocking on door]

08:46.910 --> 08:48.127
ALICIA:
Grace, that's the florist.

08:48.170 --> 08:49.171
Can you get that?

08:49.220 --> 08:50.437
Mm-hmm.

09:00.190 --> 09:01.794
[chuckles]
We're here.

09:01.840 --> 09:05.230
JACKIE:
Grace, my dear.

09:05.280 --> 09:07.145
Grandma's here
ten minutes early!

09:07.190 --> 09:09.101
Well, traffic was so good.

09:09.150 --> 09:12.062
And you never can tell
if it's going to rain.

09:12.110 --> 09:14.237
Can I get a hit of that?

09:17.290 --> 09:20.817
How are you, Mom?

09:20.860 --> 09:23.420
[soft chuckle]
I'm hunky-dory.

09:23.470 --> 09:25.028
You seem frazzled.

09:25.080 --> 09:26.775
Thanks.
It's a good thing.

09:26.820 --> 09:28.037
It's more real.

09:28.080 --> 09:29.217
Okay.
To real.

09:36.140 --> 09:38.005
Just want to check my makeup.[gasps]

09:38.050 --> 09:39.483
Oh.

09:39.530 --> 09:42.044
Grandma, they made a
mistake. Don't worry.

09:42.100 --> 09:44.443
Oh, my God,
they are

09:44.490 --> 09:47.015
just beautiful.

09:47.060 --> 09:48.015
[gaSPS]

09:48.060 --> 09:49.049
You like them?

09:49.110 --> 09:50.919
Oh.

09:50.980 --> 09:53.232
Why are we hiding
them in the bedroom?

09:53.280 --> 09:54.679
[doorbell rings, door opens]

09:54.720 --> 09:59.111
Sorry we're early,
the traffic was light.

09:59.160 --> 10:02.414
Oh, you must be Zach.

10:02.470 --> 10:03.414
Mom?

10:03.470 --> 10:05.119
Grandma likes the flowers.

10:05.160 --> 10:07.902
She's pulling them
out into the living room.

10:07.950 --> 10:09.724
[doorbell rings]

10:09.780 --> 10:11.293
I thought we had
another ten minutes.

10:15.520 --> 10:16.919
Oh, hello.

10:16.960 --> 10:18.302
You're Grace, right?

10:18.350 --> 10:19.339
I'm Hannah McCreary.

10:19.400 --> 10:20.389
Is your brother... ?

10:29.620 --> 10:31.622
[laughs]

10:36.810 --> 10:38.539
ZACH:
Mom, I want you to meet

10:38.590 --> 10:40.717
my girlfriend, Hannah.

10:42.330 --> 10:44.594
I loved that you stood
by your husband.

10:44.640 --> 10:46.596
A lot of people my age
think it's a throwback

10:46.640 --> 10:48.289
to an old kind of domesticity,

10:48.340 --> 10:51.298
but I think it's a harbinger
of a new feminism.

10:51.340 --> 10:53.388
Like Huma Abedin, you know?

10:53.430 --> 10:54.909
Women should do what they want,

10:54.950 --> 10:57.692
even if what they want
is to stand by their man.

10:57.740 --> 10:59.867
Hi.

10:59.920 --> 11:01.171
Hannah's a proctor in my dorm.

11:01.220 --> 11:02.391
Really?

11:02.440 --> 11:03.600
I know I'm older,

11:03.660 --> 11:06.128
but Zach is older in maturity
than he looks.

11:06.180 --> 11:10.059
And sometimes compatibility
is more a function

11:10.100 --> 11:13.149
of intellectual reach than
physical years, don't you think?

11:15.190 --> 11:18.273
You look relaxed.

11:18.320 --> 11:20.459
CARY:
Upside of choosing
unemployment.

11:20.500 --> 11:22.411
[chuckles]
What do you need?

11:22.460 --> 11:25.099
Do you know Jason Crouse?

11:25.160 --> 11:26.320
I do.
My old work.

11:26.380 --> 11:27.324
He dropped by.

11:27.380 --> 11:28.506
That's why I called.

11:28.550 --> 11:30.199
He's investigating
for Peter Florrick,

11:30.250 --> 11:32.593
the Richard Locke mistrial.

11:32.640 --> 11:34.289
Makes sense.

11:34.340 --> 11:36.035
They're looking
for a scapegoat.

11:36.080 --> 11:37.035
That's what he said?

11:37.080 --> 11:38.479
No, that's what I know.

11:38.520 --> 11:40.476
They're looking for
someone to point a finger at.

11:40.520 --> 11:41.475
Well, it's not me.

11:41.520 --> 11:42.475
Are you sure?

11:42.520 --> 11:43.600
We were the prosecutors.

11:43.650 --> 11:45.254
We dealt with the evidence.

11:45.310 --> 11:47.346
We didn't tank it.

11:47.400 --> 11:48.742
Yeah, in my experience,

11:48.790 --> 11:51.304
whenever there's a battle
between truth and power,

11:51.360 --> 11:52.577
truth loses.

11:57.890 --> 11:59.755
So, how long have
they been dating?I don't know.

11:59.800 --> 12:01.791
I didn't even know that they
were dating; she's like 23.

12:01.850 --> 12:03.363
VERONICA: Alicia, what are you
doing in the kitchen?

12:03.410 --> 12:04.195
Get some catering help.

12:04.240 --> 12:05.411
Mom?
[chuckles]
Mwah.

12:05.460 --> 12:06.620
What are you doing here?

12:06.680 --> 12:07.806
Jackie invited me.

12:07.850 --> 12:09.579
And I drove her.
Mom can't drive anymore.

12:09.640 --> 12:11.369
No, I chose not to.

12:11.420 --> 12:12.762
Where's the wine?

12:12.810 --> 12:14.368
Wait, Jackie invited you?

12:14.420 --> 12:15.819
Why?
You guys hate each other.

12:15.860 --> 12:18.374
Oh, Alicia, sometimes you're
so innocent about women.

12:18.430 --> 12:19.727
Pour one for me, too.

12:19.780 --> 12:21.509
She invited me

12:21.560 --> 12:23.733
so she could lord it over me
about her new husband.

12:23.780 --> 12:26.123
I mean, this is how sick in
the head your mother-in-law is.

12:26.180 --> 12:27.829
She actually thought
I'd be jealous of Howard.

12:27.870 --> 12:28.825
[chuckles]

12:28.870 --> 12:30.826
Hey, darling.
Ooh.

12:30.880 --> 12:33.041
So, I heard you
got into college.
Yeah.

12:33.100 --> 12:34.783
Who's gonna be the
smart one now, huh?

12:34.840 --> 12:36.353
And, Alicia, empty nest--

12:36.400 --> 12:38.004
that is coming up quickly
for you, isn't it?

12:38.060 --> 12:40.665
Alicia, do you think
you have enough wine?

12:40.710 --> 12:42.268
Have you seen them out there?[Veronica chuckles]

12:42.320 --> 12:43.366
They're all senior citizens.

12:43.410 --> 12:44.445
We're gonna be
the only ones drinking.

12:44.500 --> 12:45.797
[laughs]No, Zach drinks, too, now.

12:45.850 --> 12:47.806
What? Zach?
How old is Zach?

12:47.850 --> 12:49.579
I thought he was
just out of high school.

12:49.630 --> 12:51.541
That's okay, children should
learn to drink young.

12:51.590 --> 12:53.854
Italian kids drink right out of
the crib, look at them.

12:53.900 --> 12:57.370
Sis, is there
anything I should know?

13:01.910 --> 13:06.472
Hey, thanks for
doing this for Mom.

13:06.520 --> 13:08.294
Can we talk for a minute?

13:08.350 --> 13:09.829
Sure.

13:09.870 --> 13:10.859
Eli, how are you?

13:10.920 --> 13:12.956
Marissa, you look beautiful.

13:13.000 --> 13:14.740
Thank you.
I'm Dad's plus-one.

13:14.790 --> 13:15.950
Thought I'd class him up.

13:20.400 --> 13:21.924
There was a misunderstanding.

13:21.970 --> 13:23.961
Ah.

13:24.020 --> 13:25.317
So I talked to Chris Broccoli,

13:25.360 --> 13:27.885
and he had a suggestion.

13:27.930 --> 13:28.885
Neil?

13:28.930 --> 13:30.978
Yeah, the divorce lawyer.

13:31.020 --> 13:33.716
He suggested we do
a one-lavwer divorce

13:33.760 --> 13:35.546
since it's amicable.

13:35.590 --> 13:38.593
We don't have to use him if you
want to agree on someone else.

13:38.640 --> 13:40.460
One-one—one minute.
Thank you.

13:40.510 --> 13:42.899
What do you think?

13:42.950 --> 13:46.113
I think that's... smart.

13:46.170 --> 13:47.421
Good.

13:47.470 --> 13:48.778
Because I don't want
to fight with you.

13:48.820 --> 13:49.775
I know.

13:49.820 --> 13:51.822
I don't want to either.

13:53.130 --> 13:55.086
So Zach brought
a girlfriend here.

13:55.130 --> 13:57.303
Hannah.

13:57.350 --> 13:58.783
Really?

13:58.830 --> 14:02.869
She's 23 years old,
